'''John O'Neill''' (died c.1 December 1941<ref name="irishtimes1941">{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/archive/1941/1202/Pg005.html#Ar00502|title=Obituary: Mr. John O'Neill|date=2 December 1941|work=[[The Irish Times]]|page=5|accessdate=7 April 2015|subscription=Y}}</ref>) was an Irish businessman who was an [[Seanad Éireann (Irish Free State)|Irish Free State senator]] in 1925.<ref name="seanad1925">{{cite web|url=http://oireachtasdebates.oireachtas.ie/debates%20authoring/DebatesWebPack.nsf/takes/seanad1925030500005#N7|title=Public Business; Election of a Senator|date=30 March 1925|work=Seanad Éireann debates|accessdate=7 April 2015}}</ref> He was formally [[independent politician|independent]], but took a pro-[[Cumann na nGaedheal]] line.<ref name="coakley2005"/> In 1925 he was living in [[Delgany]], County Wicklow,<ref name="seanad1925"/> and described himself as a "cycle manufacturer and motor trader".<ref name="coakley2005">{{Cite journal|title=Ireland's Unique Electoral Experiment: The Senate Election of 1925 |doi=10.1080/07907180500359327 |first=John |last=Coakley |journal=Irish Political Studies |date = September 2005|volume=20 |issue=3 |pages=261–268 }}</ref> He owned O'Neill Motors,<ref name="Dunphy2000">{{cite book|last=Dunphy|first=Richard |editor=Mike Cronin and John M. Regan|title=Ireland: The Politics of Independence, 1922–49|year=2000|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|doi=10.1057/9780230535695 |isbn=9780333720509 |chapter=The Enigma of Fianna Fáil: Party Strategy, Social Classes and the Politics of Hegemony}}</ref> a Dublin garage acquired in 1959 by Ryan's Car Hire.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://archive.commercialmotor.com/article/6th-february-1959/47/mi-crograms-|title=Car Hire Acquisition|date=6 February 1959|work=Commercial Motor|page=47|accessdate=7 April 2015}}</ref>

O'Neill served on several committees and commissions on industry and commerce. During the [[First World War]] he chaired the All-Ireland Munitions and Government Supplies Committee, which tried with limited success to secure war-related contracts for Irish firms.<ref name="seanad1925"/><ref>{{cite book|last=Riordan|first=E.J.|others=historical introduction by George O'Brien|title=Modern Irish trade and industry|chapter=XI: Government Contracts; (5) Munitions of War|page=214|chapterurl=https://archive.org/stream/modernirishtrade00rioriala#page/214/mode/1up|year=1920|publisher=E.P. Dutton|location=New York}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|date=27 June 1919|title=Irish Conditions|journal=The Electrical Review|volume=84|issue=2170}}</ref> He served on [[Alexander Bruce, 6th Lord Balfour of Burleigh|Lord Balfour of Burleigh]]'s 1916–17 [[Committee on Commercial and Industrial Policy]], dissenting from its final report in particular due to Ireland-specific issues.<ref>{{cite book|author=Committee on commercial and industrial policy after the war|title=Final report|chapterurl=https://archive.org/stream/finalreportofcom00grearich#page/71/mode/1up|series=[[Command paper]]s|volume=Cd.9035|year=1918|publisher=[[HMSO]]|location=London|pages=71–72|chapter=Memorandum by Mr. J. O'Neill|ol=14007895M}}</ref> He chaired the [[First Dáil]]'s Commission of Inquiry into the Resources and Industries of Ireland,<ref name="seanad1927"/><ref name="Carty2012">{{cite book|last=Carty|first=James|title=Bibliography of Irish History 1912–1921|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=t36-BAAAQBAJ&pg=PA128|accessdate=7 April 2015|date=30 March 2012|publisher=Andrews UK Limited|isbn=9781781514832|page=128 No.1087}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Commission of Inquiry into the Resources and Industries of Ireland|title=Ad interim report on milk production|url=https://archive.org/stream/cu31924013773571#page/n6/mode/1up|edition=3rd|year=1920|location=Dublin}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Commission of Inquiry into the Resources and Industries of Ireland|title=Minutes of evidence |url=https://archive.org/stream/minutesofevidenc01comm#page/n10/mode/1up|volume=1|year=1920|page=3|chapter=First Day}}</ref> and served on the Economic Relations Committee established in 1921 by [[Robert Barton]], the Dáil's [[Minister for Economic Affairs]], to advise on the economic aspects of the negotiations for the [[Anglo-Irish Treaty]].<ref name="seanad1925"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://treaty.nationalarchives.ie/wp-content/uploads/2011/11/Barton.pdf#page=3 |title=Barton, Robert Childers|last=Dempsey|first=Pauric J.|author2=Shaun Boylan|date=November 2011|work=Treaty Exhibition|publisher=[[National Archives of Ireland]]|quote=[Barton] was made minister for economic affairs, and in that position established the economic relations committee to advise the government on the implications of the British government's financial proposals for the settlement of the Irish question, published after the truce.|accessdate=17 April 2015|format=PDF|page=3}}</ref> After independence, he advocated [[protectionism]],<ref name="Dunphy2000"/> and served on a 1923 committee planning the takeover of the [[dockyard]] at [[Haulbowline]].<ref name="seanad1925"/> In 1931 he was one of three members of the advisory committee under the Trade Loans (Guarantee) Act, 1924.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://oireachtasdebates.oireachtas.ie/debates%20authoring/debateswebpack.nsf/takes/dail1931062400029#N14|title=Trade Loans (Guarantee) (Amendment) Bill, 1931-Second Stage.|date=24 June 1931|work=Dáil Éireann debates|accessdate=7 April 2015}}</ref> He was on the 1934–38 Banking Commission which led to the creation of the [[Central Bank of Ireland]], attending 94 of its 150 meetings and subscribing to the majority report.<ref name="Dunphy2000"/><ref>{{cite book|author=Commission of Inquiry into Banking, Currency and Credit|title=Report|url=http://opac.oireachtas.ie/AWData/Library3/Library2/DL056922.pdf |pages=vi, 369, 415 |series=Official publications|volume=P.2628|date=6 August 1938|publisher=Stationery Office|location=Dublin|format=PDF}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://oireachtasdebates.oireachtas.ie/Debates%20Authoring/DebatesWebPack.nsf/takes/seanad1942092300003#N159|title=Central Bank Bill, 1942—Second Stage.|date=23 September 1942|work=Seanad Éireann debates|accessdate=7 April 2015}}</ref>

O'Neill was elected to the Seanad at a by-election on 30 March 1925 to fill the vacancy created by the death of [[George Sigerson]],<ref name=oireachtas_db>{{cite web|url=http://oireachtas.ie/members-hist/default.asp?housetype=1&HouseNum=1922&MemberID=1606&ConstID=215|title=Mr. John O'Neill|work=Oireachtas Members Database|accessdate=16 January 2016}}</ref> finishing one vote ahead of [[Patrick McCartan]].<ref name="seanad1925"/> That September, he was defeated in the [[Irish Seanad election, 1925|1925 Seanad triennial election]].<ref name="coakley2005"/> He stood unsuccessfully in the 1927 by-election to fill the vacancy created by the death of [[Stephen O'Mara (senator)|Stephen O'Mara]], finishing fifth behind [[P. J. Brady]].<ref name="seanad1927">{{cite web|url=http://oireachtasdebates.oireachtas.ie/debates%20authoring/DebatesWebPack.nsf/takes/seanad1927012600006|title=Election of Senator|date=26 January 1927|work=Seanad Éireann debates|accessdate=7 April 2015}}</ref>

